From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: ArcBoost Builder <build@arcboost.local>
Date: Sat, 9 May 2026 22:08:41 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 03/13] ArcBoost: kCircularMask decision-type flag
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Reserves bit 4 of decision_type_ for marking a split as circular (arc) rather
than linear-threshold. The arc-membership bitset rides on the existing
cat_threshold_ / cat_boundaries_ machinery, so circular splits also set
kCategoricalMask — downstream bitset-decode paths work unchanged.

A follow-up patch wires Tree::SplitCircular() (the analog of SplitCategorical)
and the storage-side helpers; this patch just lands the flag so other patches
can reference it. No behavior change yet.
---
 include/LightGBM/tree.h | 12 ++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+)

diff --git a/include/LightGBM/tree.h b/include/LightGBM/tree.h
index bc5af621..dd105e6b 100644
--- a/include/LightGBM/tree.h
+++ b/include/LightGBM/tree.h
@@ -19,6 +19,18 @@ namespace LightGBM {
 
 #define kCategoricalMask (1)
 #define kDefaultLeftMask (2)
+// ArcBoost: bit 4 marks a split as circular (arc-membership) rather than a
+// linear threshold. Circular splits also set kCategoricalMask so downstream
+// bitset-decode paths (cat_threshold_ / cat_boundaries_) can be reused
+// without modification — an arc on B bins is a contiguous bit-run with mod-B
+// wraparound, structurally identical to a categorical subset.
+//
+// Disambiguation: a split is circular iff (decision_type & kCircularMask).
+// Code that today branches on kCategoricalMask alone will continue to treat
+// circular splits as categorical (correct: same bitset decode); code that
+// needs to distinguish for reporting / feature importance must check the
+// circular bit explicitly.
+#define kCircularMask (16)
 
 /*!
 * \brief Tree model
